{
  "doc_id": "43120",
  "text": "There are currently 41 documented forms of muscular dystrophy caused by monogenic mutations. [CITATION_1] Many result in progressive deterioration of functional musculature and its replacement by noncontractile fibrotic tissue. [CITATION_2] Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD), an X-linked disease caused by disruption of the dystrophin gene, is one of the most common forms, affecting 1 in 4,000 boys. [CITATION_3] It is characterized by a progressive loss of muscle function. [CITATION_4] Dystrophin-deficient muscles are vulnerable to contraction-induced damage, which leads to repeated cycles of necrosis and regeneration that result in failed regeneration, increased fibrosis, and progressive loss of muscle function. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] In DMD patients, this results in loss of ambulation, severe muscle contractures, and, without support devices, eventual loss of ventilatory function, leading to premature death. [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] Understanding the pathophysiology of the associated fibrosis is critical for identification of novel and optimized therapeutic targets to improve both quantity and quality of life in affected individuals.",
